<h2 align=3D"left">About This Tool</h2>


<p>Systems of measuring clothes sizes evolved differently in different part=
s of the world. Now, with online international shopping widely available, w=
e often need to translate our own local size into another international sys=
tem.</p>
<div class=3D"gas_inset_article">
<!-- NTB MSC Article -->
<ins class=3D"adsbygoogle" style=3D"display: block; height: 250px;" data-ad=
-client=3D"ca-pub-9983032687302035" data-ad-slot=3D"1686702590" data-ad-for=
mat=3D"auto" data-full-width-responsive=3D"true" data-adsbygoogle-status=3D=
"done"><div id=3D"aswift_3_host" style=3D"border: none; height: 250px; widt=
h: 320px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; position: relative; visibility: visibl=
e; background-color: transparent; display: inline-block;"></div></ins>
</div>
<p align=3D"left"><b>US Size System:</b> In the US, shirt sizes for women t=
ypically range from XS to XL, with numbered dress sizes from 0 to 16 and pa=
nts sizes often listed by waist measurements in inches (e.g., 26, 28). US d=
ress and pant sizes are generally one to two sizes smaller than UK sizes an=
d run larger than Japanese sizes. For example, a US size 4 dress is equival=
ent to a UK size 8, an EU size 36, and a Japanese size 9.</p>

<p align=3D"left"><b>UK Size System:</b> UK clothing sizes for shirts typic=
ally range from 6 to 18, while pants and dress sizes are similarly numbered=
 (e.g., 8, 10, 12). UK sizes are usually two sizes larger than US sizes and=
 about one size smaller than EU sizes. For example, a UK size 12 dress corr=
esponds to a US size 8, an EU size 40, and a Japanese size 13.</p>

<p align=3D"left"><b>EU Size System:</b> The EU system uses numbers like 34=
, 36, and 38 for shirts, pants, and dresses, reflecting chest, waist, and h=
ip measurements in centimeters. EU sizes run about two sizes larger than US=
 sizes and are typically one size larger than UK sizes. For instance, an EU=
 size 38 shirt or dress corresponds to a US size 8, a UK size 10, and a Jap=
anese size 11.</p>

<p align=3D"left"><b>Japanese Size System:</b> Japanese sizes are generally=
 smaller, with shirts, pants, and dresses labeled with numbers like 7, 9, a=
nd 11, or letters like S, M, L. These sizes are typically smaller than both=
 US and EU sizes; for example, a Japanese size 9 dress is roughly equivalen=
t to a US size 4, a UK size 8, and an EU size 36. Japanese pants sizes also=
 tend to be more fitted, with smaller waist and hip measurements compared t=
o Western standards.</p>

